  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_959998412" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/959998412" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4086118-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567611029p2/4086118.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/959998412?book_show_action=true">Jun 06, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/4086118-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780552077651" href="/book/show/828504.Giovanni_s_Room">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Michael by: </span>
      Jeffrey Keeten
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=lgbt">lgbt</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=paris">paris</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=france">france</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=sexuality">sexuality</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=social-commentary">social-commentary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4086118-michael?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer959998412" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16477888149133592752">This is a tragedy of failed love in post-war Paris, featuring a protagonist as hard to judge as Camus&apos; &quot;The Stranger.&quot; The narrator, David, is a young man on an extended stay from the U.S. on parental funds, ostensibly to develop his writing skills, but in reality to play. A transient gay fling with an impoverished, artistic Bohemian leads to an idyllic cohabitation while his fiancé travels in the East. You know it didn’t last from the beginning of the book, but as the affair proceeds, you feel </span>
  <span id="freeText16477888149133592752" style="display:none">This is a tragedy of failed love in post-war Paris, featuring a protagonist as hard to judge as Camus' "The Stranger." The narrator, David, is a young man on an extended stay from the U.S. on parental funds, ostensibly to develop his writing skills, but in reality to play. A transient gay fling with an impoverished, artistic Bohemian leads to an idyllic cohabitation while his fiancé travels in the East. You know it didn’t last from the beginning of the book, but as the affair proceeds, you feel the delicious wonder of their love that is so liberating, you want it to last forever. Where so many travel tales open you to the adventure of exploring new worlds, this book sets the benchmark for a story of creating a world inside a room with the universe of two people. But then such a wrenching you are bound for. <br /><br />There is no focus on race in this tale, but the need for gays to "pass" as straight is revealed to be as much a corrupting a force as blacks considering passing as white not so long ago. And the phenomenon of internalized racism has its close parallel with the self’s importation of society’s disgust with same sex relations over much of history. I am always surprised when I learn of people who “discover” they are gay after long periods of living as straight. In this story I get some of such a reality when I learn how David has succeeded in erasing his early sexual experience with Joey at 13, a love discarded in a mental closet. <br /><br />First love is such a powerful theme in literature, but see if this little excerpt with Joey doesn’t get some special power and rank over other accounts from Baldwin’s skill and from the incident being so forbidden at the time:<br /><i>Joey raised his head as I lowered mine and we kissed, as it were by accident. Then, for the first time in my life, I was really aware of another person’s body, of another person’s smell. We had our arms around each other. It was like holding in my hand some rare, exhausted, nearly doomed bird which I ad miraculously happened to find. I was very frightened, I was sure he was frightened too, and we shut our eyes. To remember it so clearly, so painfully tonight tells me I never for an instant truly forgotten it. I feel in myself now a faint, dreadful stirring of what so overwhelmingly stirred in me then, great thirsty eat, and trembling, and tenderness so painful I thought my heart would burst. But out of this astounding, intolerable pain came joy, we have each other joy that night. It seemed, then, that a lifetime would not be long enough for me to act with Joey the act of love.</i><br /><br />And see if there isn’t something immortal here, something akin to the literary equivalent of a first climb of Everest:<br /><i>It was borne in on me: <u>But Joey is a boy.</u>. I saw suddenly the power in his thighs, in his arms, and in his loosely curled fists. The power and the promise and the mystery of that body made me suddenly afraid. The body suddenly seemed the black opening of a cavern in which I would be tortured till madness came, in which I would lose my manhood. Precisely, I wanted to know that mystery and feel that power and have that promise fulfilled through me. The sweat on my back grew cold. I grew ashamed. The very bed, in its sweet disorder, testified to vileness. I wondered what Joey’s mother would say when she saw the sheets. Then I thought of my father, who had no one in the world but me, my mother having died when I was little. A cavern opened in my mind, black, full of rumor, suggestion, of half-heard, half-forgotten, half-understood stories, full of dirty words. I thought I saw my future in that cavern. I was afraid. I could have cried, cried for shame and terror, cried for not understanding how this could have happened to me, how this could have happened <u>in</u> me.</i><br /><br />But all that is just background to the story here, but critical background. Once a person feels compelled to live a lie, some of one’s humanity inevitably gets eroded. The consequences of the moral choices and lies that David tells to Giovanni and to his future wife led me to some hateful responses, struggling all the while to find the forgiveness he was surely due. Much has changed since this was written, and much has not. There is still a frontier for anyone trying to chart the course of a bisexual identity, for, as explored recently in John Irving’s wonderful “In One Person”, they find themselves rejected or mistrusted by most gays and straights alike.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16477888149133592752" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


